  "response": "Laplace transforms are typically taught in both differential equations and Fourier analysis courses, but with different emphasis:\n\n1. Differential Equations:\n- Used primarily as a method to solve linear differential equations\n- Focuses on solving initial value problems\n- Transforms differential equations into algebraic equations\n- Especially useful for solving ODEs with initial conditions\n\n2. Fourier Analysis:\n- Discussed as a different type of integral transform\n- More theoretical approach\n- Emphasizes frequency domain representation\n- Often compared and contrasted with Fourier transforms\n\nIn most undergraduate curricula, Laplace transforms are first introduced in differential equations courses, and then further explored in more advanced signal processing or Fourier analysis courses.\n\nThe context and depth of treatment differs between these courses, with differential equations focusing more on problem-solving techniques and Fourier analysis providing a more theoretical mathematical perspective.",
